<p><strong>TheServerHost <a href="https://theserverhost.com/vps/israel">Israel KVM VPS</a> :&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>KVM Virtualization is one of the industry's most popular virtualization solutions available today. KVM is an open-source, client-server virtualization technology that supports virtualization on different types of hardware such as x86, arm, and smart cards. It provides high-end performance and great ease of use for the application which uses it. It allows both local and remote computers to work together in the same manner as if they were physically located on the same machine.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>KVM is highly useful in the deployment of virtual machines. Enterprises use it to separate physical machines from their applications and storage pools so that performance and system performance is better optimized for each instance. Enterprises can also use the same virtualization platform for different versions of the same application across multiple environments. A red hat enterprise Linux solution using key virtualization will be able to run on the latest LAMP or X Server.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;Xen is the standard hypervisor used on the Linux kernel since the 1990. Xen has been used by thousands of servers and it continues to gain popularity among users and enterprise Linux vendors. By using the Xen hypervisor, an enterprise can have a single server with the ability to run both the Linux kernel and the operating system, operating systems, and other applications.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Hypervisor support for virtual servers was first implemented in Linux distributions such as Red Hat, Fedora, and Novell. The Hyper-v hypervisor is supported on a Linux virtual platform using an open source virtualization engine called OpenVZ. This technology allows developers to use an open source operating system without the compatibility constraints that come from using a commercial hypervisor.</p>
